# .phi-scanignore — PhiScan exclusion patterns
# Syntax: gitignore-style (via Python pathspec library)
#
# Rules:
#   - Lines starting with # are comments
#   - Blank lines are ignored
#   - Patterns match relative to the repository root
#   - Trailing / matches directories only: node_modules/
#   - * matches anything except /: *.pyc
#   - ** matches any number of directories: **/test_data/
#   - ! prefix negates a pattern (re-include): !important_config.yml
#   - Leading / anchors to repo root: /build/ matches only root-level build/
#   - No leading / matches at any depth: __pycache__/ at depth 1 or depth 10
#
# Full syntax reference: phi-scan explain ignore (available Phase 2+)
#
# Intentional omissions (not excluded by default):
#   *.log  — Log files are a primary PHI leak vector in healthcare systems.
#            Excluding them would silently suppress detections in application logs.
#            Add *.log to your own .phi-scanignore if you are certain your logs
#            contain no PHI (e.g. build logs in a non-clinical repo).
#   .env   — .env files may contain hardcoded credentials or PHI values.
#            If a .env file exists in the repo it should be scanned.
#            Add .env to .gitignore to keep it out of the repo entirely.

# Dependencies
node_modules/
.venv/
venv/
__pycache__/
.tox/

# Build outputs
dist/
build/
*.egg-info/
target/

# Compiled and binary artifacts
# These are binary files — they contain no scannable plaintext and cannot hold PHI.
*.pyc
*.class
*.jar
*.war

# IDE and editor
.idea/
.vscode/
*.sw?
#*#
.*~
.DS_Store

# Version control
# .git/ is listed explicitly for clarity — pathspec does not skip hidden
# directories automatically, so this ensures git internals are never scanned.
.git/

# Binary and database files
# WARNING: *.db and *.sqlite3 suppress scanning of ALL SQLite files in the repo,
# including third-party or application databases that may contain PHI.
# PhiScan skips binary files automatically, but this exclusion prevents even
# attempting to open them. Remove these lines if you store PHI in SQLite files
# and want PhiScan to flag the presence of the database itself.
*.db
*.sqlite3

# PhiScan internal
# Audit database and runtime state written by PhiScan itself.
.phi-scanner/

# Infrastructure directories
# WARNING: .terraform/ suppresses scanning of the entire Terraform working
# directory, including .tfstate files which are known to contain secrets and
# occasionally PHI (e.g. resource names, IDs, tags with patient identifiers).
# Remove .terraform/ from this file if your Terraform state may contain PHI.
.terraform/
.serverless/
